#doc (Manual) "Measure Theory in Mathlib" =>
%%%
htmlSplit := .never
tag := "measure-theory"
%%%

Measure theory in Mathlib is a substantial part of the library, covering
sigma-algebras, measurable functions, measures, integration, and probability.
It builds on the filter framework for convergence theorems. This section
gives an overview of the main definitions and how to work with them.

# Sigma-algebras: MeasurableSpace
%%%
tag := "measurable-space"
%%%

A *sigma-algebra* (or *measurable space*) on a type `Оұ` is specified by the
typeclass `MeasurableSpace Оұ`. It tells Lean which subsets of `Оұ` are
*measurable*.

```lean
#print MeasurableSpace
-- The key field is: MeasurableSet : Set Оұ вҶ’ Prop

-- в„қ has a measurable space structure (the Borel sigma-algebra)
#check (inferInstance : MeasurableSpace в„қ)

-- The whole space and the empty set are measurable
example : MeasurableSet (Set.univ : Set в„қ) :=
  MeasurableSet.univ

example : MeasurableSet (вҲ… : Set в„қ) :=
  MeasurableSet.empty

-- Complements of measurable sets are measurable
example (s : Set в„қ) (hs : MeasurableSet s) : MeasurableSet sб¶ң :=
  hs.compl

-- Countable unions of measurable sets are measurable
#check MeasurableSet.iUnion
```

On `в„қ` (and other topological spaces), the default sigma-algebra is the
*Borel sigma-algebra*, generated by the open sets.

# Measurable functions
%%%
tag := "measurable-functions"
%%%

A function `f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ` between measurable spaces is *measurable* if the
preimage of every measurable set is measurable.

```lean
#check @Measurable
-- Measurable f : Prop
-- means: вҲҖ s, MeasurableSet s вҶ’ MeasurableSet (f вҒ»В№' s)

-- The identity function is measurable
example {Оұ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] : Measurable (id : Оұ вҶ’ Оұ) :=
  measurable_id

-- Composition of measurable functions is measurable
example {Оұ ОІ Оі : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] [MeasurableSpace ОІ]
    [MeasurableSpace Оі] (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ) (g : ОІ вҶ’ Оі)
    (hf : Measurable f) (hg : Measurable g) : Measurable (g вҲҳ f) :=
  hg.comp hf

-- Continuous functions between topological spaces (with Borel sigma-algebras) are measurable
#check @Continuous.measurable
```

Important: every continuous function is measurable (when both spaces carry
the Borel sigma-algebra), but not vice versa.

# Measures
%%%
tag := "measures"
%%%

A *measure* on a measurable space `Оұ` is a countably additive function from
measurable sets to `[0, вҲһ]`. In Mathlib, measures take values in `в„қвүҘ0вҲһ`
(the extended nonnegative reals, typed `\R\ge0\infty` or using `ENNReal`).

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.Measure
-- MeasureTheory.Measure Оұ : Type

-- A measure assigns a value in в„қвүҘ0вҲһ to each measurable set
example {Оұ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] (Ој : MeasureTheory.Measure Оұ)
    (s : Set Оұ) : в„қвүҘ0вҲһ :=
  Ој s

-- The measure of the empty set is 0
example {Оұ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] (Ој : MeasureTheory.Measure Оұ) :
    Ој вҲ… = 0 :=
  MeasureTheory.measure_empty

-- Monotonicity: if s вҠҶ t, then Ој(s) вүӨ Ој(t)
#check @MeasureTheory.measure_mono
```

# The Lebesgue measure on в„қ
%%%
tag := "lebesgue-measure"
%%%

The standard measure on `в„қ` is the *Lebesgue measure*, available as
`MeasureTheory.volume` (or via the notation `volume`).

```lean
open MeasureTheory in
-- The Lebesgue measure of an interval
#check @Real.volume_Icc
-- volume (Set.Icc a b) = ENNReal.ofReal (b - a)  (when a вүӨ b)

-- volume is a measure on в„қ
open MeasureTheory in
#check (volume : Measure в„қ)
```

# Integration
%%%
tag := "integration"
%%%

Mathlib provides the Bochner integral `вҲ« x, f x вҲӮОј` (typed `\int`), which
generalizes both the Lebesgue integral for real-valued functions and the
integral for Banach-space-valued functions.

```lean
open MeasureTheory in
-- The integral notation
#check @MeasureTheory.integral
-- вҲ« x, f x вҲӮОј : E  (where E is a Banach space)

-- Linearity of the integral
#check @MeasureTheory.integral_add
#check @MeasureTheory.integral_smul

-- Integral over an indicator function
#check @MeasureTheory.integral_indicator
```

For nonnegative functions, there is also the `вҲ«вҒ»` (lower Lebesgue integral)
taking values in `в„қвүҘ0вҲһ`:

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.lintegral
-- вҲ«вҒ» x, f x вҲӮОј : в„қвүҘ0вҲһ
```

# Convergence theorems
%%%
tag := "convergence-theorems"
%%%

The fundamental convergence theorems of measure theory are available in Mathlib:

**Monotone Convergence Theorem**: If `fвӮҖ вүӨ fвӮҒ вүӨ fвӮӮ вүӨ ...` is an increasing
sequence of nonnegative measurable functions, then
`вҲ«вҒ» x, (вЁҶ n, f n x) вҲӮОј = вЁҶ n, вҲ«вҒ» x, f n x вҲӮОј`.

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.lintegral_iSup
```

**Dominated Convergence Theorem**: If `fвӮҷ вҶ’ f` pointwise a.e., and
`|fвӮҷ| вүӨ g` a.e. for an integrable `g`, then `вҲ« x, fвӮҷ x вҲӮОј вҶ’ вҲ« x, f x вҲӮОј`.

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence
```

These theorems are stated using filters: convergence of the integrals is
expressed as `Filter.Tendsto` with respect to `Filter.atTop`.

# Probability measures
%%%
tag := "probability-measures"
%%%

A measure `Ој` is a *probability measure* if `Ој Set.univ = 1`. Mathlib uses
the typeclass `MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure Ој` for this.

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure
-- class IsProbabilityMeasure (Ој : Measure Оұ) : Prop where
--   measure_univ : Ој Set.univ = 1

-- If Ој is a probability measure, then Ој(s) вүӨ 1 for all s
example {Оұ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] (Ој : MeasureTheory.Measure Оұ)
    [MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure Ој] (s : Set Оұ) :
    Ој s вүӨ 1 := by
  calc Ој s вүӨ Ој Set.univ := MeasureTheory.measure_mono (Set.subset_univ s)
    _ = 1 := MeasureTheory.IsProbabilityMeasure.measure_univ
```

There is also `MeasureTheory.IsFiniteMeasure Ој` for finite measures and
`MeasureTheory.SigmaFinite Ој` for sigma-finite measures.

# Almost everywhere and ae-filter
%%%
tag := "ae-filter"
%%%

Many statements in measure theory hold "almost everywhere" (a.e.), meaning
outside a set of measure zero. In Mathlib, this is captured by the
*ae-filter* `MeasureTheory.Measure.ae Ој`, which is the filter of sets whose
complement has measure zero.

```lean
open MeasureTheory in
#check @Measure.ae
-- Measure.ae Ој : Filter Оұ

-- "f = g almost everywhere" means {x | f x вү  g x} has measure zero
open MeasureTheory in
example {Оұ : Type*} [MeasurableSpace Оұ] (Ој : Measure Оұ) (f g : Оұ вҶ’ в„қ) :
    f =бөҗ[Ој] g вҶ” вҲҖб¶  x in Ој.ae, f x = g x :=
  Iff.rfl
```

This is a beautiful example of the filter framework in action: "almost
everywhere" is just "eventually" with respect to the ae-filter.

# Conditional expectation
%%%
tag := "conditional-expectation"
%%%

For probability theory, Mathlib provides conditional expectation with respect
to a sub-sigma-algebra. This is an advanced topic, but the key definition is:

```lean
#check @MeasureTheory.condexp
-- condexp (m : MeasurableSpace Оұ) (Ој : Measure Оұ) (f : Оұ вҶ’ E) : Оұ вҶ’ E
```

The conditional expectation `Ој[f | m]` is the unique (a.e.) `m`-measurable
function that agrees with `f` in integral over every `m`-measurable set.

# Summary of key Mathlib API for measure theory
%%%
tag := "measure-api-summary"
%%%

| Concept | Mathlib name |
|---------|-------------|
| Sigma-algebra | `MeasurableSpace Оұ` |
| Measurable set | `MeasurableSet s` |
| Measurable function | `Measurable f` |
| Measure | `MeasureTheory.Measure Оұ` |
| Lebesgue measure | `MeasureTheory.volume` |
| Bochner integral | `вҲ« x, f x вҲӮОј` |
| Lebesgue integral | `вҲ«вҒ» x, f x вҲӮОј` |
| Probability measure | `IsProbabilityMeasure Ој` |
| Almost everywhere | `вҲҖб¶  x in Ој.ae, p x` |
| Integrable | `MeasureTheory.Integrable f Ој` |
| Conditional expectation | `MeasureTheory.condexp` |

Working with measure theory in Mathlib requires familiarity with `в„қвүҘ0вҲһ`
(extended nonnegative reals) and the filter framework. Many lemmas require
measurability or integrability hypotheses, so expect to prove these as
side goals.
